WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.023 --> 00:00:02.942
Previously on AMC's
"Better Call Saul"...

2
00:00:02.953 --> 00:00:05.246
You. as the lawyer who brought
this case to the firm...

3
00:00:05.257 --> 00:00:07.882
- we can guarantee you 20%.
- Jimmy: That will work.

4
00:00:07.893 --> 00:00:09.403
[Crying] My brother is sick!

5
00:00:09.414 --> 00:00:10.880
Unfortunately. we have an
issue we need to discuss.

6
00:00:10.882 --> 00:00:12.482
It concerns your malpractice insurance.

7
00:00:12.484 --> 00:00:14.440
Kim: I looked at the
numbers. and I can carry us.

8
00:00:14.451 --> 00:00:16.869
I'll take care of my half.
You take care of yours.

9
00:00:16.880 --> 00:00:18.904
Mr. Gatwood? Hi. Kim Wexler.

10
00:00:18.920 --> 00:00:20.253
I've got no choice.

11
00:00:20.255 --> 00:00:22.324
Hector wants to use my dad's business.

12
00:00:22.335 --> 00:00:24.301
Mike: I've got cash I can't spend.

13
00:00:24.312 --> 00:00:27.227
You opened this place to
solve a similar problem.

14
00:00:27.229 --> 00:00:28.921
Perhaps there is a way.

15
00:00:31.198 --> 00:00:33.599
[Bird chirping. vehicle approaches]

16
00:00:33.610 --> 00:00:35.588
[Brakes squeal]

17
00:00:38.602 --> 00:00:40.635
- [Engine shuts off. keys jingle]
- [Sighs]

18
00:00:45.576 --> 00:00:47.630
_

19
00:01:00.390 --> 00:01:01.799
[Car door closes]

20
00:01:06.384 --> 00:01:07.651
[Knock on door]

21
00:01:08.131 --> 00:01:11.023
Mrs. Landry. you're
looking lovely as ever.

22
00:01:11.034 --> 00:01:12.984
Jimmy McGill!

23
00:01:12.995 --> 00:01:14.960
W-What are you doing here?

24
00:01:14.971 --> 00:01:16.921
Oh. I was in the area. and I thought...

25
00:01:16.932 --> 00:01:19.799
I wonder how my favorite
former client is doing?

26
00:01:19.810 --> 00:01:21.307
And I have cookies.

27
00:01:21.331 --> 00:01:22.864
[Chuckling] Oh. you're so sweet.

28
00:01:22.866 --> 00:01:24.298
Come on in!

29
00:01:24.300 --> 00:01:25.409
Jimmy: After I made these.

30
00:01:25.420 --> 00:01:28.035
I looked down. and I thought. "Wow!

31
00:01:28.037 --> 00:01:30.358
That looks just like your Felix."

32
00:01:30.369 --> 00:01:31.424
[Chuckles]

33
00:01:31.435 --> 00:01:33.225
They do!

34
00:01:33.236 --> 00:01:35.346
You're so thoughtful.

35
00:01:35.357 --> 00:01:37.078
I was afraid you wouldn't be here.

36
00:01:37.080 --> 00:01:38.252
Thought. with that settlement money.

37
00:01:38.263 --> 00:01:41.015
you might've moved somewhere swankier.

38
00:01:41.017 --> 00:01:43.944
- What do you mean?
- The settlement.

39
00:01:43.955 --> 00:01:45.921
The Sandpiper case?

40
00:01:45.932 --> 00:01:47.488
Now. that's gotta be
wrapped up by now. right?

41
00:01:47.490 --> 00:01:51.764
Oh. that? That... that...
that... that's still years away.

42
00:01:51.775 --> 00:01:52.827
You haven't settled yet?

43
00:01:52.829 --> 00:01:55.496
No. I don't know all the
details yet. but Erin...

44
00:01:55.498 --> 00:01:59.333
uh. Erin Brill of Davis
& Main... do you know her?

45
00:01:59.344 --> 00:02:04.096
Lovely girl. [Chuckling] She
reminds me of a young Mary Martin.

46
00:02:04.107 --> 00:02:06.616
Oh. yes. I-I have met her.

47
00:02:06.627 --> 00:02:09.502
It's a... She's a
wonderful young lady. Uh...

48
00:02:09.513 --> 00:02:11.076
Well. she takes care of all of that.

49
00:02:11.087 --> 00:02:14.182
and she said there's
still a long way to go.

50
00:02:14.184 --> 00:02:16.881
But you've... received an offer. right?

51
00:02:16.892 --> 00:02:19.722
Something sent to you in writing?

52
00:02:19.733 --> 00:02:22.623
I mean. something more than
just Erin and you chatting?

53
00:02:22.625 --> 00:02:23.975
Oh.

54
00:02:27.326 --> 00:02:30.425
It's probably all here in this box.

55
00:02:30.436 --> 00:02:32.934
I can't make heads or tails of it.

56
00:02:32.936 --> 00:02:35.519
but you are welcome to look.

57
00:02:35.530 --> 00:02:36.929
You sure?

58
00:02:36.940 --> 00:02:39.370
[Chuckling] Of course. It's you.

59
00:02:40.995 --> 00:02:44.500
Well. uh. I gotta say...

60
00:02:44.511 --> 00:02:48.149
I can't blame you for getting
mixed up with all this.

61
00:02:48.151 --> 00:02:49.625
[Chuckles]

62
00:02:49.636 --> 00:02:51.268
I mean. these legal notices...

63
00:02:51.279 --> 00:02:54.455
I mean. no one really understands them.

64
00:02:54.457 --> 00:02:57.291
You know. [Chuckles]
I've got a law degree.

65
00:02:57.293 --> 00:02:59.627
And sometimes I can't even. uh...

66
00:03:03.405 --> 00:03:05.428
I can't even. uh...

67
00:03:07.026 --> 00:03:08.426
[Sighs deeply]

68
00:03:08.437 --> 00:03:10.338
[Paper rustles]

69
00:03:11.233 --> 00:03:13.107
You haven't. uh...

70
00:03:13.686 --> 00:03:15.343
accepted this?

71
00:03:15.345 --> 00:03:17.616
Erin says we should wait.

72
00:03:18.545 --> 00:03:19.780
But...

73
00:03:19.782 --> 00:03:21.444
[Chuckles]

74
00:03:21.788 --> 00:03:24.170
Erin doesn't really matter. does she?

75
00:03:24.181 --> 00:03:27.264
I mean. you're the Class Representative.

76
00:03:27.757 --> 00:03:29.190
That's a big deal.

77
00:03:29.192 --> 00:03:32.126
That means you and you alone decide.

78
00:03:32.128 --> 00:03:34.756
You're... you are the legal stand-in

79
00:03:34.767 --> 00:03:37.098
for your friends and neighbors.

80
00:03:37.100 --> 00:03:39.317
I-I don't know about all that. Jimmy.

81
00:03:39.328 --> 00:03:42.618
I-I just leave it all
to the professionals.

82
00:03:42.629 --> 00:03:44.415
Yeah. sure. sure.

83
00:03:44.426 --> 00:03:46.371
Lawyers know best. but...

84
00:03:47.059 --> 00:03:49.010
[Chuckling] I'm sorry.

85
00:03:49.012 --> 00:03:50.344
If you won the lottery.

86
00:03:50.346 --> 00:03:52.213
I mean. you'd take the lump sum. right?

87
00:03:52.215 --> 00:03:54.882
I mean. money now is
better than money later.

88
00:03:54.884 --> 00:03:57.542
- Bird in the hand!
- I suppose.

89
00:03:57.553 --> 00:03:59.620
The more time to enjoy it!

90
00:03:59.622 --> 00:04:01.055
[Chuckles]

91
00:04:01.057 --> 00:04:03.291
You really should talk to Erin.

92
00:04:03.293 --> 00:04:05.526
She knows all the ins and outs.

93
00:04:05.528 --> 00:04:07.194
[Sighs] Ins and outs.

94
00:04:07.196 --> 00:04:10.309
Yeah. Erin sure knows those. [Chuckles]

95
00:04:10.320 --> 00:04:14.103
I'll be happy to talk to Erin. uh...

96
00:04:14.114 --> 00:04:16.003
Just... I just can't help but wonder

97
00:04:16.005 --> 00:04:19.817
- if she's taking every aspect into a...
- [Knock on door]

98
00:04:20.245 --> 00:04:21.860
Oh. Jimmy.

99
00:04:21.871 --> 00:04:23.915
I completely forgot...

100
00:04:23.926 --> 00:04:26.347
I'm on my way to chair yoga.

101
00:04:26.349 --> 00:04:27.682
I'm so sorry.

102
00:04:27.684 --> 00:04:29.050
No. it's okay.

103
00:04:29.052 --> 00:04:31.852
Um. I probably should be going.

104
00:04:31.854 --> 00:04:34.228
I have a lot to do.

105
00:04:34.239 --> 00:04:37.024
[Indistinct conversation in distance]

106
00:04:38.160 --> 00:04:39.353
- [Chuckling]
- Hi.

107
00:04:39.364 --> 00:04:40.415
- Jimmy!
- Jimmy!

108
00:04:40.426 --> 00:04:43.345
- Jimmy!
- Rose. Myrtle. Helen.

109
00:04:43.730 --> 00:04:46.261
That chair yoga really works. huh?

110
00:04:46.277 --> 00:04:47.442
You all look 10 years younger.

111
00:04:47.453 --> 00:04:48.535
- Oh!
- [All chuckling]

112
00:04:48.546 --> 00:04:50.338
- You honeydripper.
- Hey. hurry up.

113
00:04:50.340 --> 00:04:51.572
It starts in five minutes.

114
00:04:51.574 --> 00:04:52.660
Do you want to come with us?

115
00:04:52.671 --> 00:04:54.542
You're welcome to. We can have guests.

116
00:04:54.544 --> 00:04:58.012
I would love to. uh. but
I'm not dressed for it.

117
00:04:58.014 --> 00:05:00.516
So I'll take a rain check.

118
00:05:00.527 --> 00:05:01.633
Certainly.

119
00:05:01.644 --> 00:05:02.995
Thanks for the cookies. Jimmy.

120
00:05:03.006 --> 00:05:05.019
- Bye. Jimmy! Good to see ya.
- Bye!

121
00:05:05.030 --> 00:05:08.398
[Vehicle passing]

122
00:05:09.692 --> 00:05:11.192
That can't be right.

123
00:05:11.194 --> 00:05:13.060
[Chuckling] Can't be right.

124
00:05:13.062 --> 00:05:14.328
[Sighs]

125
00:05:17.274 --> 00:05:20.532
17.4 total.

126
00:05:21.157 --> 00:05:22.993
33% is the common fund.

127
00:05:23.004 --> 00:05:26.228
So. on 1/15.

128
00:05:26.239 --> 00:05:28.712
15 into 17...

129
00:05:29.978 --> 00:05:31.837
carry the 2.

130
00:05:32.485 --> 00:05:35.220
One million. one hundred and sixty...

131
00:05:36.806 --> 00:05:41.962
One million. one hundred and
sixty thousand! [Chuckling]

132
00:05:42.325 --> 00:05:43.501
[Chuckles]

133
00:05:43.512 --> 00:05:45.192
Holy shit!

134
00:05:46.227 --> 00:05:50.060
♪ ♪

135
00:05:50.071 --> 00:05:55.384
<font color="#007700">Synced and corrected by Aaronnmb</font>
www.addic7ed.com

136
00:05:59.937 --> 00:06:02.105
[Indistinct conversations in distance]

137
00:06:02.116 --> 00:06:03.357
[Telephone rings in distance]

138
00:06:03.404 --> 00:06:05.271
[Elevator bell dings]

139
00:06:06.695 --> 00:06:10.063
[Motor whirring]

140
00:06:18.507 --> 00:06:20.240
- Mr. Ehrmantraut?
- Yeah.

141
00:06:20.242 --> 00:06:21.400
Sorry to keep you waiting.

142
00:06:21.411 --> 00:06:23.674
- It'll be right this way.
- [Grunts]

143
00:06:24.025 --> 00:06:26.679
Can I get you anything to
drink? Tea. water. espresso?

144
00:06:26.681 --> 00:06:28.689
No. I'm fine. Thank you.

145
00:06:29.362 --> 00:06:32.619
[Indistinct conversations.
telephone ringing]

146
00:06:42.600 --> 00:06:44.179
[Knocks on door]

147
00:06:45.039 --> 00:06:46.332
Ms. Rodarte-Quayle?

148
00:06:46.334 --> 00:06:48.336
- I have your next...
- Yes. thank you.

149
00:06:48.347 --> 00:06:50.562
Mr. Ehrmantraut. Lydia Rodarte-Quayle.

150
00:06:50.573 --> 00:06:53.312
- Mike.
- Thanks. Justin.

151
00:06:53.323 --> 00:06:57.164
Have a seat. um... Mike.

152
00:06:57.672 --> 00:06:59.429
HR sent up your start paperwork.

153
00:06:59.440 --> 00:07:02.141
I-9. W-2. Pretty standard.

154
00:07:04.352 --> 00:07:07.854
Could I have your driver's
license and Social Security card?

155
00:07:07.856 --> 00:07:09.007
Why?

156
00:07:09.018 --> 00:07:11.069
My assistant needs to make a copy.

157
00:07:12.054 --> 00:07:16.019
How does this "hire" work.
exactly? Walk me through it.

158
00:07:16.030 --> 00:07:17.964
You'll receive a paycheck from Madrigal

159
00:07:17.966 --> 00:07:19.966
in the amount of $10.000 per week.

160
00:07:19.968 --> 00:07:21.319
I believe at that rate.

161
00:07:21.330 --> 00:07:24.616
your "employment" should be
paid out in about 20 weeks.

162
00:07:24.627 --> 00:07:28.371
Mr. Fring has arranged to
cover FICA. Social Security...

163
00:07:28.382 --> 00:07:30.529
the entirety of the tax burden.

164
00:07:30.540 --> 00:07:32.841
I assume that's all right with you?

165
00:07:35.163 --> 00:07:36.616
Good. So. to that end.

166
00:07:36.618 --> 00:07:39.195
I have you down as a
"logistics consultant."

167
00:07:39.206 --> 00:07:40.941
What is that?

168
00:07:40.952 --> 00:07:44.472
It's a person who consults on logistics.

169
00:07:44.483 --> 00:07:46.077
Does it matter?

170
00:07:46.913 --> 00:07:49.796
I'm not long on logistics.

171
00:07:49.798 --> 00:07:51.671
"Security consultant" would be better.

172
00:07:51.682 --> 00:07:53.757
I used to be a cop.

173
00:07:53.768 --> 00:07:56.002
That will look better
on your "work history"

174
00:07:56.004 --> 00:07:58.398
than your current employer. SMQ Parking.

175
00:07:58.409 --> 00:08:01.234
So. you take my money.

176
00:08:01.245 --> 00:08:03.801
you run it through this
joint. and it comes out clean.

177
00:08:03.812 --> 00:08:05.445
- That it?
- Yes.

178
00:08:06.085 --> 00:08:08.085
Who knows this operation?

179
00:08:08.096 --> 00:08:10.241
You... anyone else?

180
00:08:10.252 --> 00:08:12.507
- No.
- You sure?

181
00:08:13.601 --> 00:08:17.490
May I ask. what precisely
is your concern here?

182
00:08:17.492 --> 00:08:19.273
I am concerned about what happens

183
00:08:19.284 --> 00:08:22.462
if you put my real name in your books.

184
00:08:22.929 --> 00:08:25.615
Your Madrigal is a German company.

185
00:08:25.626 --> 00:08:29.161
One thing I know about Germans
is they love a good audit.

186
00:08:30.929 --> 00:08:34.445
I oversee eight freight terminals
across Texas and the Southwest.

187
00:08:34.456 --> 00:08:37.395
Operating costs range between $800.000

188
00:08:37.406 --> 00:08:39.970
and a million dollars per week.

189
00:08:39.981 --> 00:08:43.660
All due respect. Mike. but your money?

190
00:08:43.671 --> 00:08:45.371
It's a rounding error.

191
00:08:45.382 --> 00:08:47.863
If the IRS or anyone else looks.

192
00:08:47.874 --> 00:08:49.820
you're a contractor for a
multinational corporation

193
00:08:49.831 --> 00:08:53.254
with 114.000 employees worldwide.

194
00:08:53.265 --> 00:08:55.695
You're like every other
person in this building.

195
00:08:55.697 --> 00:08:57.421
Like you?

196
00:08:58.866 --> 00:09:01.070
You think I'm not on the books?

197
00:09:01.081 --> 00:09:03.902
I am. Under my own name.

198
00:09:03.913 --> 00:09:06.873
- This the way you handled it before?
- Handled what?

199
00:09:06.875 --> 00:09:10.009
The money. For Fring's other guys.

200
00:09:10.854 --> 00:09:12.521
Other guys?

201
00:09:13.468 --> 00:09:15.985
This is the first time I've done this...

202
00:09:15.996 --> 00:09:17.296
for anyone.

203
00:09:18.632 --> 00:09:21.238
I don't know what you do. but...

204
00:09:21.249 --> 00:09:24.257
Mr. Fring must think
you're quite good at it.

205
00:09:24.259 --> 00:09:26.249
[Sighs]

206
00:09:39.898 --> 00:09:41.574
20 weeks?

207
00:09:41.576 --> 00:09:43.509
The sooner you're off
my books. the better.

208
00:09:43.511 --> 00:09:45.093
- [Intercom beeps]
- Justin?

209
00:09:52.740 --> 00:09:55.334
Can you make a copy of
these. please? Thank you.

210
00:09:57.607 --> 00:09:59.099
[Door closes]

211
00:10:00.605 --> 00:10:02.052
What?

212
00:10:04.226 --> 00:10:06.631
This is a very nice office.

213
00:10:07.102 --> 00:10:08.576
Thank you.

214
00:10:11.740 --> 00:10:15.082
Seem to be risking a
lot for a drug dealer.

215
00:10:15.093 --> 00:10:16.706
"Drug dealer"?

216
00:10:19.381 --> 00:10:20.747
[Scoffs]

217
00:10:20.749 --> 00:10:23.483
If that's all you think he is...

218
00:10:24.250 --> 00:10:26.823
then you don't know Gustavo Fring.

219
00:10:37.022 --> 00:10:38.834
[Sighs]

220
00:10:42.771 --> 00:10:46.085
[Pen scratches]

221
00:10:46.096 --> 00:10:48.307
Howard: Let me understand you...

222
00:10:48.309 --> 00:10:50.398
you're proposing to double our premiums

223
00:10:50.409 --> 00:10:53.646
on every one of our
practicing attorneys?

224
00:10:54.289 --> 00:10:55.915
Man: We know this is abrupt...

225
00:10:55.917 --> 00:10:58.151
new issues have come to light.

226
00:10:58.153 --> 00:11:00.028
"New issues"?

227
00:11:00.039 --> 00:11:02.410
You mean Mr. McGill's
testimony at the Bar?

228
00:11:02.421 --> 00:11:03.956
That's a part of it. yes.

229
00:11:03.958 --> 00:11:06.246
After 25 years of paying full premiums.

230
00:11:06.257 --> 00:11:08.309
I can count on one hand
the number of our claims.

231
00:11:08.320 --> 00:11:10.324
Woman: This is an underwriting
decision... that's all.

232
00:11:10.335 --> 00:11:11.931
You shouldn't take it personally.

233
00:11:11.933 --> 00:11:13.633
Man: In some special circumstances.

234
00:11:13.635 --> 00:11:15.435
we have been known to extend a rider.

235
00:11:15.437 --> 00:11:16.669
What kind of rider?

236
00:11:16.671 --> 00:11:18.538
Woman: A senior.
management-level partner

237
00:11:18.540 --> 00:11:20.540
who would supervise Charles' work.

238
00:11:20.542 --> 00:11:23.155
attend court and client
meetings with him.

239
00:11:23.166 --> 00:11:24.466
review filings.

240
00:11:24.477 --> 00:11:25.610
Man: The few times we've done this.

241
00:11:25.621 --> 00:11:27.266
it's been for clients
with a high probability

242
00:11:27.277 --> 00:11:29.532
of catastrophic health
failure as a precaution.

243
00:11:29.543 --> 00:11:32.126
What you're saying is that
for any case Charles takes on.

244
00:11:32.137 --> 00:11:34.321
another partner would
be tied up. as well.

245
00:11:34.332 --> 00:11:35.732
and we don't bill a penny more?

246
00:11:35.743 --> 00:11:37.514
This is ludicrous.

247
00:11:37.525 --> 00:11:40.154
The insurance industry
is heavily regulated.

248
00:11:40.165 --> 00:11:41.712
I can think of a dozen infractions

249
00:11:41.723 --> 00:11:44.055
- right here off the top of my head.
- Mr. McGill...

250
00:11:44.064 --> 00:11:46.665
You're hoping we'll
either find another carrier

251
00:11:46.667 --> 00:11:48.498
or cut you an enormous check.

252
00:11:48.509 --> 00:11:49.709
Win-win for you!

253
00:11:49.720 --> 00:11:51.903
I assure you. neither
is going to happen.

254
00:11:51.905 --> 00:11:53.733
What will happen is very simple...

255
00:11:53.744 --> 00:11:55.295
you're going to do right by us

256
00:11:55.306 --> 00:11:57.041
or we will compel you to do so.

257
00:11:57.052 --> 00:11:59.644
- What do you mean by "compel"?
- You know exactly what I mean.

258
00:11:59.646 --> 00:12:02.514
If you're threatening litigation.
I'm afraid this meeting is over.

259
00:12:02.525 --> 00:12:04.135
Then it's over.

260
00:12:04.814 --> 00:12:06.462
Thank you for your time.

261
00:12:06.482 --> 00:12:09.033
Mr. Hamlin. Mr. McGill.

262
00:12:11.324 --> 00:12:13.088
[Door creaks]

263
00:12:19.166 --> 00:12:21.155
All right. Where do we begin?

264
00:12:21.166 --> 00:12:23.702
Francis should start
digging into regulations.

265
00:12:23.704 --> 00:12:26.338
I'm sorry I don't have the code sections

266
00:12:26.340 --> 00:12:27.772
at my fingertips just now.

267
00:12:27.774 --> 00:12:29.574
Let's pull a team of associates

268
00:12:29.576 --> 00:12:32.774
and get them looking at every
angle of injunctive relief.

269
00:12:32.785 --> 00:12:34.129
- Before close of business...
- [Glass thumps lightly]

270
00:12:34.140 --> 00:12:36.514
... we're going to hit Santa
Rosa with a demand letter

271
00:12:36.516 --> 00:12:38.283
that'll make their heads spin.

272
00:12:38.285 --> 00:12:40.352
[Chuckles] Odds are. inside a week.

273
00:12:40.354 --> 00:12:42.215
they'll be sitting at the table again.

274
00:12:42.226 --> 00:12:44.121
- [Liquid pouring]
- And if not...

275
00:12:44.124 --> 00:12:46.890
well. we've never
shied away from a fight.

276
00:12:46.901 --> 00:12:48.334
[Decanter thumps lightly]

277
00:12:50.751 --> 00:12:52.709
Chuck. do you remember Al McConnell?

278
00:12:52.720 --> 00:12:54.599
Of course. Helluva litigator.

279
00:12:54.601 --> 00:12:56.064
Retired now. isn't he?

280
00:12:56.075 --> 00:12:58.373
He's a professor at UNM now.

281
00:12:58.384 --> 00:13:01.373
Wrote a fantastic book on
SCOTUS during Reconstruction.

282
00:13:01.375 --> 00:13:02.607
Fascinating stuff.

283
00:13:02.609 --> 00:13:03.759
Okay...

284
00:13:03.770 --> 00:13:06.467
I was talking to him. and he mentioned

285
00:13:06.478 --> 00:13:09.420
he'd love you to come
speak to his One-Ls.

286
00:13:09.431 --> 00:13:12.501
Maybe make it a regular
thing. if you wanted.

287
00:13:12.630 --> 00:13:13.963
[Scoffs]

288
00:13:13.974 --> 00:13:15.754
What are you talking about. Howard?

289
00:13:15.756 --> 00:13:17.928
What I'm saying is...

290
00:13:17.939 --> 00:13:20.792
maybe it's time to hang up your spurs.

291
00:13:21.314 --> 00:13:23.185
Become partner emeritus...

292
00:13:23.196 --> 00:13:25.764
leave your name on the firm
but focus on your legacy.

293
00:13:25.766 --> 00:13:29.201
You always said you wanted to
work on the Commerce Clause...

294
00:13:29.212 --> 00:13:30.912
you can write the book on it.

295
00:13:30.923 --> 00:13:33.757
And no longer be a practicing lawyer.

296
00:13:35.524 --> 00:13:38.178
Chuck. there's more to life than this.

297
00:13:38.189 --> 00:13:41.012
That day is far in the future. Howard.

298
00:13:41.014 --> 00:13:43.814
And I don't appreciate the suggestion.

299
00:13:45.579 --> 00:13:47.485
What if it's not a suggestion?

300
00:13:47.487 --> 00:13:48.665
Meaning? [Glass thumps]

301
00:13:48.676 --> 00:13:51.589
Meaning. if enough people
tell you that you're drunk.

302
00:13:51.591 --> 00:13:53.858
maybe it's time to sit down.

303
00:13:56.495 --> 00:13:59.874
You want me to retire
over this... insurance?!

304
00:13:59.885 --> 00:14:01.315
It's not just the insurance.

305
00:14:01.326 --> 00:14:04.160
That's the straw that
broke the camel's back.

306
00:14:05.518 --> 00:14:08.206
So this is about my condition.

307
00:14:08.488 --> 00:14:09.870
Look!

308
00:14:10.543 --> 00:14:11.870
Look!

309
00:14:14.263 --> 00:14:15.908
You see?

310
00:14:16.909 --> 00:14:18.817
[Chuckling] See?

311
00:14:18.819 --> 00:14:20.385
I'm better!

312
00:14:20.823 --> 00:14:23.190
[Chuckling] Howard. I'm fine!

313
00:14:26.948 --> 00:14:29.453
This is not what "fine" looks like.

314
00:14:29.464 --> 00:14:31.112
[Sighs]

315
00:14:31.659 --> 00:14:33.325
[Lamp thuds]

316
00:14:33.336 --> 00:14:35.867
Chuck. you are the best
legal mind I've ever known.

317
00:14:35.869 --> 00:14:37.469
Hands down.

318
00:14:38.089 --> 00:14:40.551
But your decision-making has become...

319
00:14:40.562 --> 00:14:42.182
unpredictable.

320
00:14:43.076 --> 00:14:46.581
And I can't be partners with
someone whose judgment I don't trust.

321
00:14:51.381 --> 00:14:52.800
Chuck...

322
00:14:55.079 --> 00:14:59.161
[Indistinct conversations]

323
00:14:59.172 --> 00:15:00.831
[Door closes]

324
00:15:04.034 --> 00:15:07.812
This right here is the
Texas-New Mexico border.

325
00:15:07.823 --> 00:15:08.953
[Grunts]

326
00:15:08.964 --> 00:15:13.000
Now. all of my wells are square...

327
00:15:13.011 --> 00:15:15.007
on the Texas side.

328
00:15:15.018 --> 00:15:18.226
When I negotiated for the
mineral and property rights.

329
00:15:18.237 --> 00:15:22.445
the surveyors said that the
next nearest pool extended to...

330
00:15:26.494 --> 00:15:28.112
about here.

331
00:15:28.123 --> 00:15:29.569
Right.

332
00:15:29.580 --> 00:15:31.791
But... after some extraction.

333
00:15:31.802 --> 00:15:34.651
the west wall of the salt dome gave way.

334
00:15:34.662 --> 00:15:37.069
opening up another pool
that extends... what...

335
00:15:37.080 --> 00:15:38.728
100 yards over the border?

336
00:15:38.730 --> 00:15:40.252
That's about the size of it. yeah.

337
00:15:40.270 --> 00:15:43.038
And now you have New Mexico
rights holders to deal with.

338
00:15:43.541 --> 00:15:45.447
You know. they should get
profit on what's theirs.

339
00:15:45.458 --> 00:15:47.447
but now I've got two
states coming after me

340
00:15:47.458 --> 00:15:49.658
for taxes on each and every gallon.

341
00:15:51.032 --> 00:15:53.010
No equipment crosses the border?

342
00:15:53.021 --> 00:15:54.620
No. ma'am.

343
00:15:54.638 --> 00:15:57.096
Nothing below the surface. like the...

344
00:15:58.182 --> 00:15:59.939
What... is it a drill bit?

345
00:15:59.941 --> 00:16:02.682
It would be the sucker rod at
this point. but no. none of that.

346
00:16:02.693 --> 00:16:04.477
Only on the Texas side.

347
00:16:04.479 --> 00:16:07.980
But that's not stopping New
Mexico from trying to bleed me.

348
00:16:08.340 --> 00:16:10.581
You said on the phone
you have a solution.

349
00:16:11.886 --> 00:16:14.284
You don't negotiate a lease
with the rights holders.

350
00:16:14.295 --> 00:16:16.864
- You offer to pay them damages.
- Damages?

351
00:16:16.875 --> 00:16:19.005
For diminishing their resource.

352
00:16:19.020 --> 00:16:22.615
A significant fraction of the
value of the New Mexico portion.

353
00:16:22.626 --> 00:16:24.833
but without paying for
the rights themselves.

354
00:16:25.233 --> 00:16:27.224
So a kind of a payoff.

355
00:16:28.434 --> 00:16:30.380
Then you don't get hit with the taxes.

356
00:16:30.391 --> 00:16:32.524
You think you can make that fly?

357
00:16:32.535 --> 00:16:35.036
If someone came to me with this offer...

358
00:16:35.047 --> 00:16:36.909
I'd sure as hell take it.

359
00:16:36.911 --> 00:16:39.378
[Chuckling] Wish I'd called you sooner.

360
00:16:39.950 --> 00:16:41.685
Way they're makin' noise.

361
00:16:41.696 --> 00:16:44.333
if I don't get this thing wrapped
up by the end of the quarter.

362
00:16:44.344 --> 00:16:47.626
I'm pretty sure the tax
boys are gonna take me apart.

363
00:16:47.637 --> 00:16:50.138
And that's two weeks from now?

364
00:16:52.567 --> 00:16:54.093
I can do it by then.

365
00:16:54.095 --> 00:16:55.661
Really?

366
00:16:55.663 --> 00:16:57.551
If we can get all the
rights holders in one place.

367
00:16:57.562 --> 00:17:00.096
I can walk them through
what we're proposing.

368
00:17:00.107 --> 00:17:02.268
If they're smart. they'll go for it.

369
00:17:02.270 --> 00:17:03.769
Well. hot damn.

370
00:17:06.415 --> 00:17:09.298
Kevin said you were a miracle
worker. but I didn't believe him.

371
00:17:09.309 --> 00:17:11.110
I'm startin' to.

372
00:17:11.112 --> 00:17:14.513
Yeah. well. let me work that miracle
first. then we'll talk. [Chuckles]

373
00:17:14.515 --> 00:17:15.948
You know the way outta here?

374
00:17:15.950 --> 00:17:19.329
I got a drillhead that's acting up on me

375
00:17:19.340 --> 00:17:21.887
out on the north forty I gotta check.

376
00:17:21.889 --> 00:17:23.355
Yeah. I'm good.

377
00:17:23.357 --> 00:17:24.720
You need anything from me.

378
00:17:24.731 --> 00:17:26.423
- you got my cell. Call me.
- [Engine starts]

379
00:17:26.434 --> 00:17:27.884
Will do.

380
00:17:30.671 --> 00:17:34.039
[Machinery creaking]

381
00:17:43.110 --> 00:17:45.244
[Car door closes. engine starts]

382
00:17:46.781 --> 00:17:48.439
[Recorder clicks]

383
00:17:48.450 --> 00:17:51.582
Billy Gatwood meeting
notes. Contact Gatwood Oil.

384
00:17:51.593 --> 00:17:54.934
Get names and numbers for
New Mexico rights holders...

385
00:17:57.004 --> 00:17:59.535
[Wheels grinding]

386
00:17:59.546 --> 00:18:01.043
Shit!

387
00:18:06.395 --> 00:18:08.062
[Machinery creaking]

388
00:18:48.357 --> 00:18:53.166
[Car creaking]

389
00:19:00.821 --> 00:19:02.688
No. no. no. no!

390
00:19:02.690 --> 00:19:04.823
No. no. no! Shit!

391
00:19:06.794 --> 00:19:08.193
[Brakes squeal]

392
00:19:08.195 --> 00:19:09.526
[Sighs]

393
00:19:12.795 --> 00:19:14.956
[Machinery creaking]

394
00:19:15.836 --> 00:19:18.730
[Breathing deeply]

395
00:19:23.010 --> 00:19:25.003
[Seat belt clicks]

396
00:19:25.014 --> 00:19:27.147
[Engine starts]

397
00:19:28.519 --> 00:19:29.617
[Recorder clicks]

398
00:19:29.628 --> 00:19:32.680
Continuing notes from
Gatwood Oil meeting.

399
00:19:32.691 --> 00:19:34.933
Contact rights holders.

400
00:19:34.944 --> 00:19:36.933
- begin scheduling.
- [Gearshift clicks]

401
00:19:39.987 --> 00:19:43.026
[Machinery creaking]

402
00:19:43.037 --> 00:19:45.581
- [Les McCann's "McCanna" plays]
- [Tires squeal]

403
00:19:54.353 --> 00:19:56.387
[Engine shuts off. music stops]

404
00:20:00.681 --> 00:20:02.114
Howard!

405
00:20:03.161 --> 00:20:04.472
[Sighs]

406
00:20:04.483 --> 00:20:08.520
- What are you doing here. Jimmy?
- We have business to discuss.

407
00:20:08.522 --> 00:20:10.422
Is this about Chuck?

408
00:20:10.424 --> 00:20:12.224
Who?

409
00:20:12.226 --> 00:20:14.903
If you actually have business.
then call my secretary.

410
00:20:14.914 --> 00:20:17.629
I did. She stonewalled
me. as if you didn't know.

411
00:20:17.631 --> 00:20:19.087
Sandpiper.

412
00:20:19.098 --> 00:20:21.200
- What about it?
- It's time to settle.

413
00:20:21.202 --> 00:20:22.816
I-I saw the current offer.

414
00:20:22.827 --> 00:20:25.722
The clients make their losses
back. plus a solid chunk of change.

415
00:20:25.733 --> 00:20:26.886
[Sighs]

416
00:20:26.897 --> 00:20:28.737
Not that it's any of your business.

417
00:20:28.748 --> 00:20:31.537
but we project a final number
far higher than the current offer.

418
00:20:31.548 --> 00:20:33.350
I get it. I get it. You hold out.

419
00:20:33.361 --> 00:20:35.748
maybe you squeeze a grand
more for each client.

420
00:20:35.759 --> 00:20:38.006
Meanwhile. HHM nets a few million.

421
00:20:38.030 --> 00:20:40.878
You know. you're screwing the
clients for your own benefit.

422
00:20:40.889 --> 00:20:43.889
Oh. so now you're
worried about the clients?

423
00:20:43.891 --> 00:20:45.506
It's the right thing
to do. and you know it.

424
00:20:45.517 --> 00:20:47.026
Please.

425
00:20:47.037 --> 00:20:49.895
All you care about is
your share of the payout.

426
00:20:49.897 --> 00:20:51.077
[Chuckles]

427
00:20:51.088 --> 00:20:53.162
It's like talking to Gollum.

428
00:20:53.173 --> 00:20:56.066
You're transparent. And pathetic.

429
00:20:56.077 --> 00:20:57.503
[Briefcase thumps lightly]

430
00:20:57.505 --> 00:20:59.412
You want a handout?

431
00:21:00.873 --> 00:21:01.998
Here.

432
00:21:04.078 --> 00:21:05.303
Huh?

433
00:21:06.480 --> 00:21:08.284
Next time...

434
00:21:08.295 --> 00:21:10.115
why don't you bring a tin cup?

435
00:21:10.117 --> 00:21:12.030
It'd be more honest.

436
00:21:13.521 --> 00:21:16.121
Listen. Howard. settle
this and settle it now.

437
00:21:16.123 --> 00:21:17.889
It's in everyone's best interests!

438
00:21:17.900 --> 00:21:19.958
Meaning it's in your best interests.

439
00:21:19.960 --> 00:21:21.927
And if we don't. what are you gonna do?

440
00:21:21.929 --> 00:21:23.662
Peel off some members of the class.

441
00:21:23.664 --> 00:21:25.566
leak some insider info to Schweikart?

442
00:21:25.577 --> 00:21:27.766
Oh. I doubt it. I know you're low enough

443
00:21:27.768 --> 00:21:29.635
to do something like that.
but you're too damn greedy.

444
00:21:29.637 --> 00:21:30.877
- [Elevator plays melody]
- You do any of that.

445
00:21:30.888 --> 00:21:33.182
and you'll be jeopardizing your payday.

446
00:21:34.175 --> 00:21:36.324
You'll get your damn money.

447
00:21:36.335 --> 00:21:38.127
You're just gonna have to wait for it.

448
00:21:39.680 --> 00:21:42.214
[Machinery creaking]

449
00:21:42.216 --> 00:21:44.583
[Lighter clicking]

450
00:21:58.966 --> 00:22:02.544
[Clicking continues]

451
00:22:13.539 --> 00:22:16.345
[Cellphone buzzing]

452
00:22:21.989 --> 00:22:23.440
[Cellphone beeps]

453
00:22:25.001 --> 00:22:26.867
_

454
00:22:27.643 --> 00:22:30.463
_

455
00:22:30.487 --> 00:22:33.338
_

456
00:22:33.565 --> 00:22:37.292
_

457
00:22:38.565 --> 00:22:41.151
_

458
00:22:41.162 --> 00:22:44.913
_

459
00:22:44.924 --> 00:22:46.588
_

460
00:22:47.268 --> 00:22:50.229
_

461
00:22:50.292 --> 00:22:54.635
_

462
00:22:54.917 --> 00:22:57.284
_

463
00:23:05.655 --> 00:23:07.186
_

464
00:23:14.265 --> 00:23:16.023
_

465
00:23:17.139 --> 00:23:18.561
Don Hector...

466
00:23:18.572 --> 00:23:21.436
_

467
00:23:26.731 --> 00:23:29.598
♪ ♪

468
00:23:31.009 --> 00:23:32.591
Don Hector?

469
00:23:32.593 --> 00:23:34.845
[Groaning]

470
00:23:36.330 --> 00:23:40.306
♪ ♪

471
00:23:47.503 --> 00:23:49.841
[Panting]

472
00:23:49.843 --> 00:23:52.981
♪ ♪

473
00:23:55.983 --> 00:23:59.318
[Panting continues]

474
00:23:59.320 --> 00:24:03.224
♪ ♪

475
00:24:06.073 --> 00:24:09.979
_

476
00:24:10.041 --> 00:24:11.923
_

477
00:24:12.010 --> 00:24:13.815
_

478
00:24:17.438 --> 00:24:20.841
♪ ♪

479
00:24:26.410 --> 00:24:28.917
[Boz Scaggs' "Lowdown" plays]

480
00:24:30.824 --> 00:24:34.691
[Squeaking]

481
00:24:36.171 --> 00:24:39.539
[Music continues]

482
00:24:59.064 --> 00:25:02.903
[Indistinct conversation in distance]

483
00:25:05.018 --> 00:25:06.635
Irene: Well. we go around about.

484
00:25:06.658 --> 00:25:09.197
you know. six times. I think.

485
00:25:09.227 --> 00:25:13.705
I think we're... Yeah.
I think... I think so.

486
00:25:14.728 --> 00:25:16.189
I know!

487
00:25:16.200 --> 00:25:18.000
This is so good for you.

488
00:25:18.002 --> 00:25:19.244
Hello. ladies.

489
00:25:19.255 --> 00:25:20.703
Good morning.

490
00:25:20.705 --> 00:25:22.138
- Hi! Jimmy!
- Hi. Jimmy.

491
00:25:22.140 --> 00:25:23.506
Jimmy!

492
00:25:23.508 --> 00:25:26.075
Oh. y-you... you girls
go on a little bit.

493
00:25:26.077 --> 00:25:27.986
I'll... I'll catch up with you.

494
00:25:27.997 --> 00:25:29.229
- Jimmy!
- [Laughs]

495
00:25:29.240 --> 00:25:30.525
Wow. Irene!

496
00:25:30.536 --> 00:25:32.815
Fancy running into
you twice in one week.

497
00:25:32.817 --> 00:25:34.250
How lucky am I?

498
00:25:34.252 --> 00:25:35.603
Y-You're a mall-walker?

499
00:25:35.614 --> 00:25:37.614
- I had no idea!
- Me?

500
00:25:37.625 --> 00:25:39.388
Oh. yeah. Big time.

501
00:25:39.390 --> 00:25:41.657
I mean. it's great for cardio.

502
00:25:41.659 --> 00:25:45.452
Hamstrings. glutes. I-T band.

503
00:25:45.463 --> 00:25:47.030
I'm a huge mall-walker.

504
00:25:47.041 --> 00:25:48.874
Been out of the game for awhile.

505
00:25:48.885 --> 00:25:50.733
Developed this damn plantar fasciitis.

506
00:25:50.735 --> 00:25:52.401
- Mnh. Mnh.
- Hurts like a bear.

507
00:25:52.403 --> 00:25:54.806
Oh. I'm so sorry to hear about that.

508
00:25:54.817 --> 00:25:56.684
[Grunts] Well. hey.

509
00:25:56.695 --> 00:25:58.674
I got the cure right here.

510
00:25:59.728 --> 00:26:01.043
Pow!

511
00:26:01.045 --> 00:26:04.714
These have a special
gel and resistance coils

512
00:26:04.716 --> 00:26:05.948
and buncha stuff.

513
00:26:05.950 --> 00:26:08.002
It's like walkin' on pillows.

514
00:26:08.013 --> 00:26:11.053
Well. they... they...
they look comfortable.

515
00:26:11.055 --> 00:26:12.455
You like 'em?

516
00:26:12.457 --> 00:26:15.725
Well. they... they're quite stylish.

517
00:26:15.727 --> 00:26:18.048
Hey. y'know what? [Chuckles]

518
00:26:18.059 --> 00:26:20.348
I bought a pair for my
girlfriend. and they don't fit her.

519
00:26:20.359 --> 00:26:22.465
And the store has this...
wouldn't you know it?...

520
00:26:22.467 --> 00:26:24.633
- no-refunds policy.
- Oh.

521
00:26:24.635 --> 00:26:26.097
What size are you?

522
00:26:27.042 --> 00:26:29.863
7 1/2. 7 1/2.

523
00:26:29.889 --> 00:26:31.508
[Inhales sharply]

524
00:26:31.519 --> 00:26:33.863
Oh. there we go.

525
00:26:34.545 --> 00:26:36.379
- [Grunts]
- [Trunk closes]

526
00:26:36.381 --> 00:26:40.116
[Young-Holt Unlimited's
"Soulful Strut" plays]

527
00:26:41.452 --> 00:26:42.818
How does that feel?

528
00:26:42.820 --> 00:26:44.120
Oh!

529
00:26:45.366 --> 00:26:48.234
- Oh. I-I see what you mean. They...
- [Chuckles]

530
00:26:48.245 --> 00:26:52.555
They are so nice. and
they fit like a dream!

531
00:26:52.566 --> 00:26:55.398
But I-I can't take
these for free. Jimmy.

532
00:26:55.400 --> 00:26:57.063
Oh. please.

533
00:26:57.074 --> 00:26:59.611
There is one thing you could do for me?

534
00:26:59.622 --> 00:27:01.122
What's that?

535
00:27:01.441 --> 00:27:03.097
Don't tell the other
folks I gave 'em to ya.

536
00:27:03.108 --> 00:27:05.597
I don't want to look like
I'm playing favorites.

537
00:27:06.110 --> 00:27:08.770
- My lips are sealed.
- Then you go and enjoy those.

538
00:27:08.781 --> 00:27:10.075
I'm gonna go get my heart rate back up.

539
00:27:10.086 --> 00:27:11.825
- Oh. thank you!
- And I'll see you later.

540
00:27:11.843 --> 00:27:14.100
Thank you so much. Jimmy!

541
00:27:14.111 --> 00:27:15.516
[Sighs]

542
00:27:15.567 --> 00:27:16.914
[Sighs]

543
00:27:16.925 --> 00:27:19.025
[Herb Alpert & The Tijuana
Brass Band's "Popcorn" plays]

544
00:27:21.614 --> 00:27:23.146
[Sighs]

545
00:27:23.157 --> 00:27:25.255
... Right hand. friends...
the hand of love.

546
00:27:25.622 --> 00:27:27.296
Now. watch. and I'll show
you the story of life.

547
00:27:27.298 --> 00:27:29.424
You got some questions.
It's only natural.

548
00:27:29.435 --> 00:27:32.601
And the truth is. if Irene settles...

549
00:27:32.603 --> 00:27:34.603
you'd get some money.

550
00:27:35.950 --> 00:27:39.333
But. I mean. it's not like
you guys need it. right?

551
00:27:39.844 --> 00:27:42.575
On the other hand. I did
get a look at their offer.

552
00:27:42.586 --> 00:27:45.330
I don't want to speak
out of school. but...

553
00:27:45.341 --> 00:27:47.283
it's. uh... [Whistles]

554
00:27:48.028 --> 00:27:52.114
But I mean. hey. everyone's
situation is different.

555
00:27:52.528 --> 00:27:55.036
Maybe Irene just doesn't need the money.

556
00:27:55.060 --> 00:27:56.959
I mean. I don't know for a fact. but...

557
00:27:56.961 --> 00:27:59.989
when you see someone
buying nice new things...

558
00:28:00.000 --> 00:28:02.164
- Like those shoes.
- ... like those shoes.

559
00:28:02.166 --> 00:28:03.646
Uh-huh.

560
00:28:04.168 --> 00:28:06.469
Ah. I mean. those must
have cost a pretty penny.

561
00:28:06.471 --> 00:28:08.145
I mean. if she can afford those.

562
00:28:08.156 --> 00:28:09.805
she's walkin' on easy street.

563
00:28:09.807 --> 00:28:12.223
And there's something else...

564
00:28:12.473 --> 00:28:14.254
y'know. The lawyers.

565
00:28:14.265 --> 00:28:15.981
I mean...

566
00:28:16.043 --> 00:28:18.699
that's the lawyer's
share of the settlement.

567
00:28:18.710 --> 00:28:22.402
And your share is...
boop!... this much. Doo!

568
00:28:22.413 --> 00:28:27.456
If Irene holds out. the
lawyers get this much more...

569
00:28:27.458 --> 00:28:31.113
and you are gonna get this much more.

570
00:28:31.124 --> 00:28:33.407
Doesn't seem like much difference.

571
00:28:33.449 --> 00:28:36.069
I know. but that's how it works.

572
00:28:36.080 --> 00:28:37.813
And Irene knows it. too.

573
00:28:37.824 --> 00:28:40.032
I mean. the lawyers
have explained it to her.

574
00:28:40.043 --> 00:28:42.723
It's crazy. but it's all up to Irene.

575
00:28:42.754 --> 00:28:45.474
After all. she is the
Class Representative.

576
00:28:45.476 --> 00:28:48.077
Does that mean that she gets more?

577
00:28:48.079 --> 00:28:49.645
[Sighs] No. No.

578
00:28:49.647 --> 00:28:52.856
Just means in the eyes of
the court. she's special.

579
00:28:52.867 --> 00:28:56.318
She's like your
congressman or ambassador.

580
00:28:56.320 --> 00:28:58.187
Rose: Is there anything we can do?

581
00:28:58.189 --> 00:29:02.102
No. No. You can't do anything.

582
00:29:02.113 --> 00:29:03.526
I can't do anything.

583
00:29:03.528 --> 00:29:04.942
[Inhales deeply]

584
00:29:04.953 --> 00:29:06.562
Only Irene.

585
00:29:06.564 --> 00:29:08.264
[Exhales deeply]

586
00:29:08.266 --> 00:29:11.066
[Breathes deeply] She
probably knows what's best.

587
00:29:11.068 --> 00:29:14.236
I'm sure she's taking
your feelings into account.

588
00:29:14.238 --> 00:29:16.005
Hey. look at the big picture.

589
00:29:16.007 --> 00:29:19.031
Who needs money when you
got the moral high ground?

590
00:29:19.844 --> 00:29:21.443
[Breathes deeply]

591
00:29:25.421 --> 00:29:27.067
Yoo-hoo!

592
00:29:27.078 --> 00:29:28.593
Rose!

593
00:29:29.353 --> 00:29:30.835
Helen!

594
00:29:31.781 --> 00:29:33.747
Ladies?!

595
00:29:33.758 --> 00:29:35.695
Ladies!

596
00:29:41.411 --> 00:29:46.117
[Johnny Hates Jazz's "Shattered
Dreams" plays in distance]

597
00:29:49.445 --> 00:29:50.940
[Insects chirping]

598
00:29:50.942 --> 00:29:53.429
[Vehicle approaches]

599
00:29:54.162 --> 00:29:55.762
[Gearshift clicks]

600
00:29:55.773 --> 00:29:58.047
- [Dog barking in distance]
- [Engine shuts off]

601
00:29:58.049 --> 00:29:59.390
[Vehicle door closes]

602
00:30:00.418 --> 00:30:03.015
[Engine revving in distance]

603
00:30:07.673 --> 00:30:11.460
[Woman speaking Spanish on television]

604
00:30:11.462 --> 00:30:13.162
[TV shuts off]

605
00:30:13.164 --> 00:30:15.831
[Dog barking in distance]

606
00:30:15.833 --> 00:30:18.064
[Floorboards creaking]

607
00:30:18.075 --> 00:30:19.681
Ignacio?

608
00:30:19.692 --> 00:30:21.509
- _
- [Chuckles]

609
00:30:23.244 --> 00:30:25.561
_

610
00:30:25.572 --> 00:30:27.343
- [Chuckles]
- _

611
00:30:27.345 --> 00:30:28.829
[Sighs]

612
00:30:29.033 --> 00:30:30.572
_

613
00:30:40.625 --> 00:30:42.213
Papa...

614
00:30:44.784 --> 00:30:47.401
_

615
00:30:47.698 --> 00:30:49.307
_

616
00:30:50.073 --> 00:30:51.487
_

617
00:30:51.565 --> 00:30:54.932
_

